"""
mkt-christ | Exodus | chapters 28-29 | 89 verses (all missing)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-exodus-28-29-fill.py

Key Christological types:
- 28:12,29: Aaron bears the 12 names on shoulders/heart -> Christ intercedes by name (Heb 7:25; John 17)
- 28:17-20: Breastpiece gemstones -> Rev 21:19-20 (same stones as new Jerusalem foundations)
- 28:35: Bells heard as Aaron enters -> Christ's approach accepted, not fatal (Heb 10:19-22)
- 28:38: Aaron bears the guilt of sacred gifts -> Christ bears the guilt of imperfect worship
- 29:7: Anointing oil poured on head -> Christ as the Anointed One (Acts 10:38; Ps 133)
- 29:10-14: Sin offering bull burned outside camp -> Heb 13:11-12 (Jesus suffered outside the gate)
- 29:20: Blood on ear/thumb/toe -> whole-body consecration of the new-covenant high priest
- 29:29-30: Garments pass to each generation -> Heb 7:23-25 (Christ's permanent priesthood needs no successor)
- 29:38-41: Tamid (daily offering) -> Heb 7:27 (he does this once for all, not daily)
- 29:42-46: Covenant-dwelling formula -> John 1:14; Rev 21:3
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EXODUS = {
  "28": {
    "1": "<p>Aaron is called out from among the Israelites for priestly office — not self-appointed but divinely summoned. Hebrews 5:4-5 uses the same logic to establish Christ's high priesthood: 'No one takes this honor on himself, but he receives it when called by God, just as Aaron was' — then immediately: 'In the same way, Christ did not take on himself the glory of becoming a high priest. But God said to him, You are my Son...' The Aaron-pattern of divine call provides the typological framework within which the Son's eternal appointment is understood.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Make sacred garments for your brother Aaron to give him dignity and honor.' The vestiture confers dignity (kavod) and honor (tifaret) on the one who wears it. Philippians 2:9-11: 'God exalted him to the highest place and gave him the name that is above every name.' The high priest's dignified vestments are the type of the glorified humanity of the risen Christ — the human nature that was stripped at the cross is now clothed in indestructible resurrection glory. The sacred garments anticipate the white garments of the victorious Christ (Rev 1:13-16).</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Tell all the skilled workers to whom I have given wisdom in such matters that they are to make garments for Aaron.' The craftsmen work with divinely given wisdom (chokhmah). The parallel in the new covenant is the Spirit-given gifts that build the church: 'To each one the manifestation of the Spirit is given for the common good' (1 Cor 12:7). The tabernacle is built by Spirit-empowered craftsmen; the church, the new temple, is built by Spirit-gifted workers each contributing their part to the single body (Eph 4:11-16).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The list of priestly garments: breastpiece, ephod, robe, woven tunic, turban, and sash. The comprehensive vestiture of the high priest covers the whole person — from head (turban) to body (tunic) to waist (sash) — signifying the total consecration of the priest for service. Christ's high-priestly qualification is similarly total: he is 'holy, blameless, pure, set apart from sinners, exalted above the heavens' (Heb 7:26). No partial consecration — every aspect of his humanity is set apart for the priestly work.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The materials — gold, blue, purple, scarlet yarn, and fine linen — are the same materials used for the tabernacle veil (26:31) and the outer screen (27:16). The color sequence represents a theological gradient: gold (divine glory), blue (heavenly), purple (royal), scarlet (sacrificial blood), fine linen (human purity). Christ unites all these registers: he is the divine glory enfleshed, the heavenly king who came to earth, the royal Son who shed his blood, the sinless human ('fine linen of righteous acts,' Rev 19:8) who is our great High Priest.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The ephod is made of gold and colored yarns — a work of a 'skilled craftsman' (<em>choshev</em>, literally 'thinker-artisan'). The ephod served as an oracular garment (Judg 8:27; 1 Sam 23:9-12) — the device through which divine guidance was sought. Christ as the final word of God (Heb 1:1-2) replaces the ephod's oracular function: 'In the past God spoke to our ancestors through the prophets... but in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son.' The ephod-oracle gives way to the Son-oracle who is himself the Word.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Two shoulder pieces of the ephod attached at its corners so it can be fastened. The shoulder in Hebrew imagery is the place of government and burden-bearing: 'The government will be on his shoulders' (Isa 9:6). The high priest's ephod, fastened at the shoulders, is the type of the royal-priestly authority that rests on the Messiah's shoulders. He bears the weight of governance (messianic king) and the weight of intercession (high priest) simultaneously — roles the Aaronic priesthood always held separately.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The waistband of the ephod — of one piece with it. The unity of the ephod and its waistband represents the integrated nature of the high-priestly office. In Christ, the priestly and kingly functions are organically united — not two offices awkwardly combined but one person who is, by nature, both Son-of-David-king and Melchizedekian-priest (Ps 110:1-4; Heb 7:1-3). Zechariah 6:13 explicitly anticipates this: 'It is he who will build the temple... and he will be clothed with majesty and will sit and rule on his throne. And he will be a priest on his throne.'</p>",
    "9": "<p>Two onyx stones, engraved with the names of the twelve sons of Israel. The twelve names of the covenant people are borne on the high priest's shoulders into the divine presence. Jesus in John 17 prays for his disciples by name and by situation — the high-priestly prayer is the NT equivalent of Aaron carrying the names before God. 'He always lives to intercede for them' (Heb 7:25): the perpetual intercession of Christ before the Father is the antitype of Aaron bearing the twelve names into the holy place.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Six names on one stone, six on the other, in birth order. The precise, complete enumeration — no tribe left out, each in its proper place — is the type of Christ's individualized, non-generic intercession. He does not intercede for a vague category called 'the saved' but for specific persons: 'I pray for them. I am not praying for the world, but for those you have given me' (John 17:9). And later: 'I pray also for those who will believe in me through their message' (John 17:20). Every name is on the breastpiece.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The names engraved 'like a seal' (<em>pituchei chotam</em>) — permanent, official, indelible. The image of the seal on the high priest's stones anticipates Paul's language about the Spirit's sealing of believers: 'Having believed, you were marked in him with a seal, the promised Holy Spirit' (Eph 1:13). The believer is as permanently and officially marked as the name engraved on the high priest's stone — not written in sand but cut in stone, carried before God on the shoulders of the eternal priest.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Aaron is to bear the names before the LORD on his two shoulders as a memorial.' The high priest is the living memorial — his body carries the names of the people into the divine presence as he performs the sacrificial work. Christ in his resurrection body bears the marks of the cross — 'the marks of the Lord Jesus' (Gal 6:17) — as the permanent memorial of the sacrifice he made for his people. His intercession at the Father's right hand is grounded in what his body accomplished: 'Because of the blood of his cross' (Col 1:20).</p>",
    "13": "<p>Gold filigree settings for the onyx stones. The stones are secured in the most valuable and workmanlike setting. The security of the high priest's memorial stones is the type of the security of those whom Christ bears before God: 'I give them eternal life, and they shall never perish; no one will snatch them out of my hand' (John 10:28). The gold filigree that holds the stones in place is the type of the unbreakable setting in which the Father holds those the Son intercedes for.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Two braided chains of pure gold, like ropes, attached to the filigree settings. The chains connect the breastpiece (intercession) to the shoulder settings (bearing). The connection between advocacy and presence is structural in the high-priestly vestments. Jesus's intercessory work is grounded in his atoning work — he intercedes 'on the basis of' the cross (Heb 9:12): it is because he 'entered the most holy place once for all by his own blood' that he now 'lives to intercede' (Heb 7:25).</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Fashion a breastpiece for making decisions' (<em>choshen mishpat</em> — literally 'breastpiece of judgment/decision'). The breastpiece is the instrument of divine guidance and judicial decision — the oracle worn over the heart. Christ is 'the same yesterday and today and forever' (Heb 13:8) — the one through whom God's final word of decision and judgment has come. Hebrews 4:12-13: 'the word of God... judges the thoughts and attitudes of the heart'; Christ as the Word incarnate is himself the living breastpiece of divine judgment over humanity.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The breastpiece is to be 'square — a span long and a span wide — and folded double.' The square shape suggests completeness and equal-sided justice; the doubling suggests fullness. In Rev 21:16, the new Jerusalem is a perfect cube — equal in length, width, and height — the ultimate sacred space where the divine presence dwells fully. The square breastpiece is the embryonic form of the cubic holy-of-holies (1 Kings 6:20) which is the type of the perfect sacred space of the new creation.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The first row of stones on the breastpiece: carnelian (<em>odem</em>), chrysolite (<em>pitdah</em>), and beryl (<em>bareketh</em>). These same stones appear in the description of Eden's covering cherub in Ezekiel 28:13 and in the foundations of the new Jerusalem in Revelation 21:19-20. The high-priestly breastpiece connects the paradise of Eden (the beginning) through the Sinai covenant (the center) to the new Jerusalem (the end) — a single gemological thread running through the entire redemptive narrative.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The second row: turquoise (<em>nofech</em>), lapis lazuli (<em>sapir</em>), and moonstone (<em>yahalom</em>). The lapis lazuli appears in Ezekiel's vision of the divine throne (Ezek 1:26; 10:1) and in Exodus 24:10 (the pavement of sapphire under YHWH's feet when Moses and the elders ate with him). The breastpiece worn over Aaron's heart thus includes the stone of the divine throne — the high priest's very vestment contains a fragment of the vision of God's glory.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The third row: jacinth (<em>leshem</em>), agate (<em>shevo</em>), and amethyst (<em>achlamah</em>). The purple and violet tones of amethyst belong to the royal color range of the vestments (blue, purple, scarlet). The priestly breastpiece is simultaneously royal — the priest before God is also a king, anticipating the one who is 'King of kings and Lord of lords' (Rev 19:16) and who makes his people 'a kingdom and priests to serve his God and Father' (Rev 1:6).</p>",
    "20": "<p>The fourth row: chrysolite (<em>tarshish</em>), onyx (<em>shoham</em>), and jasper (<em>yashfeh</em>). The jasper stone appears as the first foundation of the new Jerusalem (Rev 21:19) and as the appearance of the one on the throne (Rev 4:3: 'had the appearance of jasper and ruby'). The breastpiece thus ends with a stone that, in Revelation's vision, represents the very appearance of God — the high priest's vestment, worn over his heart, points to the divine glory that it covers and mediates.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'There are to be twelve stones, one for each of the names of the sons of Israel, each engraved like a seal with the name of one of the twelve tribes.' The names on the breastpiece are the names over the high priest's heart — not just on his shoulders (v.12) but over his heart. The distinction between shoulder-bearing and heart-bearing is significant: the shoulders speak of intercessory work (bearing the weight); the heart speaks of intercessory love. Christ bears his people both with the strength of his priestly work and with the love of his heart (John 13:1: 'having loved his own who were in the world, he loved them to the end').</p>",
    "22": "<p>Braided chains of pure gold for the breastpiece. The chains that bind the breastpiece to the ephod and to the shoulders are the structural elements that keep the heart-memorial in its proper place before God. Paul in Romans 8:38-39 expresses the chains that connect the believer to God: 'neither death nor life, neither angels nor demons, neither the present nor the future... will be able to separate us from the love of God that is in Christ Jesus our Lord.' The chains of gold are the type of the unbreakable bonds of divine love.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Gold rings at the corners of the breastpiece attach the chains. The structural redundancy — multiple rings, multiple chains, connections at multiple points — ensures the breastpiece cannot slip or fall out of place. The intercession of Christ has the same structural redundancy: the Father's election, the Son's atonement, the Spirit's sealing, and Christ's ongoing intercession all work together to ensure that none who are given to Christ will be lost (John 6:39; 10:28-29; Rom 8:28-30).</p>",
    "24": "<p>The gold chains attach to the rings at the corners of the breastpiece. Each connection point is secure. The chain-and-ring imagery of attachment is reflected in Peter's warning about false teachers who 'have escaped the corruption of the world' but are then tangled again — contrasted with the true chains that bind believers to Christ through genuine transformation (2 Pet 1:4). The gold chains of the breastpiece represent the real, structural attachment of the people to their high priest — not superficial but built into the very vestments.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The other ends of the chains attach to the filigree settings on the shoulder pieces of the ephod. The breastpiece hangs between the shoulder-work and the heart — between the bearing of names (shoulder) and the carrying of names over the heart. This double attachment means that the memorial before God is both a matter of strength (shoulders = priestly work) and of love (heart = priestly affection). Christ's intercession is not merely official duty but arises from love: 'I pray for them' (John 17:9) — not a legal obligation but a heart-engagement.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Two more gold rings at the other two corners of the breastpiece, on the inside edge. The double-ring structure at each corner distributes the load, preventing any single point of failure. The priestly work of Christ is similarly structurally redundant: 'by two unchangeable things, in which it is impossible for God to lie, we who have fled to take hold of the hope set before us may be greatly encouraged' (Heb 6:18). The divine oath and the divine promise are the two rings that secure the breastpiece of hope.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Rings on the bottom of the shoulder pieces, connected to the breastpiece's waistband. The connecting structure becomes increasingly complex — each connection made doubly secure. The Epistle to the Hebrews similarly elaborates the multiple guarantees of Christ's high priesthood: the oath of Ps 110:4, the resurrection, the indestructible life, the permanent priesthood. The accumulation of guarantees is not redundancy for its own sake but the reflection of the gold-chains-and-rings structure of the high-priestly vestments.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The rings of the breastpiece are tied to the rings of the ephod with blue cord, connecting the breastpiece to the waistband so it will not swing away. The breastpiece must remain directly over the heart — not free to swing out of place. The concern is that the names of the people should always remain over the high priest's heart. Christ's intercession is permanent and continuous — 'he always lives to intercede for them' (Heb 7:25). The blue cord that keeps the breastpiece from swinging away is the type of the unending, constant nature of the Son's mediation.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'Whenever Aaron enters the holy place, he will bear the names of the sons of Israel over his heart on the breastpiece of decision as a continual memorial before the LORD.' The culminating verse of the breastpiece instruction: the names are over the heart, the approach to God is regular ('whenever'), the bearing is personal (Aaron himself), and the purpose is memorial intercession. Hebrews 7:25: 'He always lives to intercede for them' — the 'always' of Christ's intercession is the antitype of the 'whenever Aaron enters' — not periodic but perpetual, because the risen high priest never leaves the divine presence.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'Also put the Urim and the Thummim in the breastpiece, so they may be over Aaron's heart whenever he enters the presence of the LORD. Thus Aaron will always bear the means of making decisions for the Israelites over his heart before the LORD.' The Urim and Thummim — 'lights and perfections' or 'yes and no' (from LXX) — are the binary oracular device by which YHWH communicated his will in the period before written prophecy. Christ as the final Word of God (Heb 1:1-2) replaces the Urim and Thummim: 'In the past God spoke... through the prophets at many times and in various ways, but in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son.' The oracle has become incarnate; the divine will is no longer accessed through a breastpiece but through a Person.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'Make the robe of the ephod entirely of blue cloth.' The robe — all blue (<em>t'khelet</em>) — is the color of heaven and the covenant (Num 15:38-40: the blue thread on tassels to remind Israel of the commandments). Christ in Revelation 1:13 is described 'dressed in a robe reaching down to his feet' — the priestly robe of the eternal high priest. The all-blue robe beneath the colorful ephod layers the heavenly identity under the sacrificial work: the one who comes to earth in the colorful vestments of incarnate priesthood is first and last the heavenly Son.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The woven collar around the robe's neck opening, like a soldier's armor coat, so it will not tear. The robe 'must not tear' — the integrity of the high-priestly vestment is protected. John 19:24 notes that the soldiers cast lots for Jesus's tunic 'which was seamless, woven in one piece from top to bottom,' and decided not to tear it. The seamless tunic of Jesus is widely read as the type of the high-priestly robe that must not be torn — the high priest's vestment that is preserved whole even in the hour of crucifixion.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Pomegranates of blue, purple, and scarlet yarn around the hem of the robe, with gold bells between them. The pomegranate, with its many seeds enclosed in one skin, is a traditional symbol of the covenant community — one people with many members united under one covering. The bells sound as the priest moves. Together, the pomegranates (the people) and the bells (the sound of presence) speak of the priestly vocation: gathering the people (pomegranates) and announcing the approach of God (bells).</p>",
    "34": "<p>The alternating gold bells and pomegranates around the hem. The pattern of gold bells and pomegranates creates a rhythmic alternation of divine sound and human/community symbol. The worship of the new-covenant community follows the same alternating pattern: divine word (the bell, the proclamation) and human response (the pomegranate, the gathered community). Liturgy is this back-and-forth — God speaks (bell), the people respond (pomegranate) — the pattern stitched into the hem of the high-priestly robe.</p>",
    "35": "<p>'Aaron must wear it when he ministers. The sound of the bells will be heard when he enters the holy place before the LORD and when he comes out, so that he will not die.' The bells signal the high priest's approach so that his entry is known and prepared — so that the holiness of God does not consume him unannounced. Hebrews 10:19-22 describes the new-covenant boldness that replaces this mortal anxiety: 'We have confidence to enter the most holy place by the blood of Jesus... let us draw near.' The bells' function — warning of the potentially lethal approach — is abolished in Christ, who opens permanent, confident access to the divine presence.</p>",
    "36": "<p>'Make a plate of pure gold and engrave on it as you would engrave a seal: HOLY TO THE LORD.' The <em>tzitz</em> (golden plate) engraved with <em>qodesh laYHWH</em> — 'Holy to YHWH' — is the culminating element of the high-priestly vestiture. The high priest's very forehead declares the identity of his master and the purpose of his service. Zechariah 14:20-21 uses this same inscription eschatologically: 'On that day HOLY TO THE LORD will be inscribed on the bells of the horses... every cooking pot in Jerusalem and Judah will be holy to the LORD.' The inscription on the high priest's forehead is the seed of the universal holiness that pervades the new creation.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The golden plate is attached by a blue cord to the front of the turban. The turban (crown-equivalent for the high priest, since priests do not wear military crowns) bears the declaration of holiness at the most visible and noble point — the forehead. Jesus is the 'Holy One of God' (John 6:69; Mark 1:24) — his holiness is not a garment he wears but his very nature. The <em>tzitz</em> on Aaron's forehead declares what Aaron mediates; the person of Christ is what the <em>tzitz</em> points to.</p>",
    "38": "<p>'It will be on Aaron's forehead, and he will bear the guilt involved in the sacred gifts the Israelites consecrate, whatever their sacred gifts may be. It will be on Aaron's forehead continually so that they will be acceptable to the LORD.' The high priest bears the <em>avon ha-kodashim</em> — the guilt of the holy things. Even Israel's best worship is tainted — the sacred gifts carry residual guilt that must be absorbed by the high priest before they are accepted. This is the deepest type of the cross: Christ bears not only Israel's sins but the imperfection of their best offerings, so that even their imperfect worship is accepted because of his perfect mediation.</p>",
    "39": "<p>'Weave the tunic of fine linen and make the turban of fine linen. The sash is to be the work of an embroiderer.' Fine linen (<em>shesh</em>) is the material of the holy — used for the tabernacle curtains, the priestly garments, and in Revelation 19:8 for the bridal garment of the church: 'Fine linen stands for the righteous acts of God's holy people.' The fine-linen tunic of the high priest is the type of the righteousness in which Christ clothes his people — not their own righteousness but his (Phil 3:9; Zech 3:4-5).</p>",
    "40": "<p>'Make tunics, sashes and caps for Aaron's sons to give them dignity and honor.' All the priests are dignified — not just the high priest. The NT extends high-priestly dignity to the whole community: 'You are a chosen people, a royal priesthood, a holy nation' (1 Pet 2:9). Every believer in Christ is clothed in priestly dignity. The tunics of Aaron's sons, conferring honor on those who serve in the outer courts, are the type of the white garments given to all who overcome (Rev 3:5; 7:9).</p>",
    "41": "<p>'After you put these clothes on your brother Aaron and his sons, anoint and ordain them (<em>male' yadam</em> — fill their hands). Consecrate them so they may serve me as priests.' The ordination formula — <em>male' yad</em> (fill the hand) — is the investiture with office. Acts 10:38: 'God anointed Jesus of Nazareth with the Holy Spirit and power.' The Spirit's anointing of Jesus at his baptism is the NT ordination — his priestly and royal office is conferred by the Father's anointing, not by a human ceremony. The filling of the hand (with the sacrificial portions to wave before God) is the type of the filling of the Spirit that equips for priestly service.</p>",
    "42": "<p>'Make linen undergarments as a covering for the body, reaching from the waist to the thigh.' The undergarments address the most basic concern: the covering of the body's vulnerability before God. The nakedness that Adam and Eve covered with fig leaves (Gen 3:7) was addressed at the sanctuary gate: YHWH made them garments of skin (Gen 3:21). The priestly linen undergarments continue this covering — the exposure of the human before the holy God requires divine provision of covering. Christ's righteousness is the ultimate covering: 'clothe yourselves with the Lord Jesus Christ' (Rom 13:14).</p>",
    "43": "<p>'Aaron and his sons must wear them whenever they enter the tent of meeting or approach the altar to minister in the holy place, so that they will not incur guilt and die.' The vestments are not decorative but protective — their absence means death. The clothing of Christ's righteousness is similarly protective, not merely aesthetic: 'without holiness no one will see the Lord' (Heb 12:14). The linen undergarments that prevent priestly death are the type of the imputed righteousness that allows sinners to approach the holy God without being consumed.</p>"
  },
  "29": {
    "1": "<p>'This is what you are to do to consecrate them, so they may serve me as priests: Take a young bull and two rams without defect.' The ordination ceremony requires perfect animals — the standard of <em>tamim</em> (without defect) that applies to all sacrificial animals and ultimately to Christ (1 Pet 1:19). The bull is for the sin offering (v.14); the two rams are for the burnt offering (v.18) and the ordination offering (v.22). The full range of sacrificial categories — atonement, consecration, and total self-giving — is required to inaugurate the priesthood.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Unleavened bread in three forms: plain loaves, loaves mixed with oil, and wafers spread with oil. The three forms of unleavened bread accompany the ordination sacrifices, representing the purity (no leaven), the anointing (oil mixed), and the dedication (oil spread) of the priestly service. Paul's description of the new-covenant life as 'unleavened' (1 Cor 5:7-8) — 'the bread of sincerity and truth' — is the antitype: the whole life of the new-covenant community is to be the bread of consecration, without the leaven of the old life.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The bread is presented in a basket along with the bull and the two rams. The combination of grain offering and animal sacrifice — the fruit of human labor (bread) and the blood of substitutionary death (animals) — in the ordination ceremony prefigures the Lord's Supper: bread (the fruit of labor) alongside the 'blood of the covenant' (the animal-sacrifice antitype). The ordination meal of Exod 29 becomes, in the NT, the covenant meal that ordains the new-covenant community to its priestly service.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Bring Aaron and his sons to the entrance to the tent of meeting and wash them with water.' The washing at the entrance before ordination is the type of baptism. Hebrews 10:22: 'Let us draw near to God with a sincere heart and with the full assurance that faith brings, having our hearts sprinkled to cleanse us from a guilty conscience and having our bodies washed with pure water.' The priestly washing at the tent's entrance is the OT form of the new-covenant washing that inaugurates priestly service — the baptism into Christ that cleanses and consecrates.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Take the garments and dress Aaron with the tunic, the robe of the ephod, the ephod itself and the breastpiece. Fasten the ephod on him by its skillfully woven waistband.' The vestition — dressing the newly washed priest in the sacred garments — is the type of 'putting on Christ.' Galatians 3:27: 'All of you who were baptized into Christ have clothed yourselves with Christ.' The baptism (v.4, washing) followed by the vestition (v.5, garments) maps directly onto the NT pattern: baptism followed by the clothing of Christ's righteousness. The new believer puts on the high-priestly vestments of Christ as their ordained covering.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Put the turban on his head and attach the sacred emblem (<em>nezer ha-kodesh</em>) to the turban.' The <em>nezer</em> (consecration-crown/diadem) is the royal-priestly headpiece — the word used for the nazirite's separation (Num 6:7) and for the king's crown (Ps 89:39). The turban with the golden plate combines the priestly function (covering the head for service) with the kingly marker (the crown-equivalent). Christ wears both: 'On his robe and on his thigh he has this name written: KING OF KINGS AND LORD OF LORDS' (Rev 19:16); 'he is... priest on his throne' (Zech 6:13).</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Take the anointing oil and anoint him by pouring it on his head.' The anointing of Aaron by oil poured over the head is the foundational act of priestly consecration — the source of the title <em>kohen ha-mashiach</em> (the anointed priest). <em>Mashiach</em> (anointed) is the root of both 'Messiah' and 'Christ' (<em>Christos</em>). Acts 10:38: 'God anointed Jesus of Nazareth with the Holy Spirit and power.' Psalm 133 likens the Spirit's anointing to the oil poured on Aaron's head: 'It is like precious oil poured on the head... running down on Aaron's beard, down on the collar of his robe.' The Spirit poured at Jesus's baptism (Matt 3:16) is the fulfillment of the ordination oil.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Bring his sons and dress them in tunics.' The sons receive the same vestiture as the father — derived priestly honor. In Christ, all believers receive derived priestly honor: 'To him who loves us and has freed us from our sins by his blood, and has made us to be a kingdom and priests to serve his God and Father' (Rev 1:5-6). The sons who receive tunics from the anointed father are the type of the church that receives priestly dignity from the anointed Son.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'The priesthood is theirs by a lasting ordinance (<em>chukat olam</em>).' The Aaronic priesthood is established as a permanent institution. Hebrews 7:23-24 makes the contrast: 'Now there have been many of those priests, since death prevented them from continuing in office; but because Jesus lives forever, he has a permanent priesthood.' The <em>chukat olam</em> of the Aaronic line is fulfilled and surpassed in the permanent priesthood of the Son — 'permanent' not because of hereditary succession but because 'he always lives.'</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Bring the bull to the front of the tent of meeting, and Aaron and his sons shall lay their hands on its head.' The laying on of hands (<em>samach</em>) identifies the offerer with the animal — the guilt of the one is transferred to the other. Paul in 2 Corinthians 5:21: 'God made him who had no sin to be sin for us.' The ordination sin offering is the type: the priestly hands lay their guilt on the head of the substitute; at the cross, the Father makes the Son to be sin — the ultimate hand-laying of transferred guilt.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Slaughter it in the LORD's presence at the entrance to the tent of meeting.' The sin offering is killed before YHWH — in the divine presence, not concealed. The crucifixion is similarly public: 'Jesus Christ was clearly portrayed as crucified' (Gal 3:1). The atoning death happens in the open, before God and the watching world, not in a private transaction. The public nature of the ordination sin offering anticipates the 'open demonstration' of the cross (Rom 3:25-26).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Some of the bull's blood put on the horns of the altar, the rest poured at the base. The blood applied to the altar's horns consecrates the instrument of sacrifice; the blood poured at the base grounds the atonement in the earth. Hebrews 9:21-22: Moses 'sprinkled with the blood both the tabernacle and everything used in its ceremonies... without the shedding of blood there is no forgiveness.' The altar's blood-anointing is the type of the consecration that Christ's blood accomplishes — he 'through the eternal Spirit offered himself unblemished to God' and thereby 'cleanse[s] our consciences... so that we may serve the living God' (Heb 9:14).</p>",
    "13": "<p>The fat of the internal organs, liver lobe, and kidneys — the richest portions — burned on the altar. The fat is YHWH's portion in every sacrifice (Lev 3:16: 'all the fat is the LORD's'). The giving of the best, the richest, the most vital portion to God is the type of the total consecration that the gospel demands: 'I urge you, brothers and sisters, in view of God's mercy, to offer your bodies as a living sacrifice, holy and pleasing to God — this is your true and proper worship' (Rom 12:1).</p>",
    "14": "<p>'But burn the bull's flesh and its hide and its intestines outside the camp. It is a sin offering.' The sin offering is burned outside the camp — not at the altar but removed from the sacred precincts, bearing the defilement away from the holy space. Hebrews 13:11-13: 'The high priest carries the blood of animals into the most holy place as a sin offering, but the bodies are burned outside the camp. And so Jesus also suffered outside the city gate to make the people holy through his own blood. Let us, then, go to him outside the camp, bearing the disgrace he bore.' The site of Jesus's crucifixion — outside Jerusalem's walls — is the spatial fulfillment of the sin-offering's burning outside the camp.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Take one of the rams, and Aaron and his sons shall lay their hands on its head.' The second sacrifice is the burnt offering — the ram wholly consumed. The laying of hands transfers the worshippers' consecration to the animal, which gives its whole life to God. Romans 12:1 calls for 'living sacrifices' — the new-covenant equivalents of the burnt offering that give the whole self to God. But the ground of this total consecration is Christ's own total self-offering, which the burnt offering anticipates.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Slaughter the ram and splash its blood against the sides of the altar. The blood splashed on the altar's sides is the blood of consecration — not the blood of atonement (like the sin offering) but the blood of dedication. Ephesians 5:2: 'Live a life of love, just as Christ loved us and gave himself up for us as a fragrant offering and sacrifice to God.' The burnt offering's blood of dedication points to Christ's self-offering as an act of love and total consecration to the Father's will.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The ram is cut into pieces, the internal organs and legs washed, then reassembled with the head. The detailed cutting and washing of the sacrifice ensures its purity — nothing unclean is burned on the altar. The concern for the integrity of the sacrifice points to the requirement of Christ's perfection as the sacrifice: 'a lamb without blemish or defect' (1 Pet 1:19). The washing and inspection of the sacrifice is the OT form of the NT declaration that the sacrifice must be 'perfect' to accomplish atonement.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Then burn the entire ram on the altar. It is a burnt offering to the LORD, a food offering (<em>isheh</em>), an aroma pleasing to the LORD (<em>re'ach nicho'ach laYHWH</em>).' The totally consumed burnt offering produces the 'aroma pleasing to YHWH' — the divine acceptance of the total self-giving. Ephesians 5:2 applies this formula directly to Christ: 'Christ loved us and gave himself up for us as a fragrant offering and sacrifice to God' — using precisely the LXX language of <em>osme euodias</em> (sweet aroma) that translates <em>re'ach nicho'ach</em>. Christ's sacrifice is the burnt offering that satisfies completely.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Take the other ram, and Aaron and his sons shall lay their hands on its head.' The third animal — the ordination ram (<em>eil hammilu'im</em>, the ram of filling) — is the distinctive sacrifice of the ordination ceremony. The laying of hands on the ordination ram expresses not primarily guilt-transfer but identification: the priests are identified with the sacrifice that initiates their ministry. Jesus identifies himself with the sacrifice that initiates his priestly ministry: 'For their sakes I consecrate myself' (John 17:19) — the Gethsemane consecration that leads to the cross.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Slaughter it, take some of its blood and put it on the lobes of the right ears of Aaron and his sons, on the thumbs of their right hands and on the big toes of their right feet.' The blood applied to ear, thumb, and big toe — the whole person consecrated from hearing (ear) to action (thumb/hand) to walking (toe/foot). Hebrews 10:5-7 (citing Ps 40) applies this total-person consecration to Christ: 'A body you prepared for me... I have come to do your will, my God' — the ear that hears the Father's will, the hands that do the priestly work, the feet that walk the path of obedience even to death.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'And take some of the blood on the altar and some of the anointing oil and sprinkle it on Aaron and his garments and on his sons and their garments.' The combination of blood and anointing oil on the high priest — the sacrifice (blood) and the Spirit (oil) together consecrate him for ministry. This combination points to Christ: the one anointed by the Spirit at baptism (the oil) who then offered himself in blood at the cross. The two elements — Spirit and blood — are the twin qualifications of the eternal high priest (1 John 5:6-8 cites these as witnesses).</p>",
    "22": "<p>The fat, fat tail, fat around the organs, liver lobe, kidneys, and the right thigh are taken from the ordination ram — the choicest portions. The right thigh (the wave offering portion) is the priest's share in subsequent peace offerings. The priest participates in the very sacrifice he offers — he eats from what he waves before God. Jesus both offers the sacrifice and participates in its benefits: 'for their sakes I consecrate myself, that they too may be truly consecrated' (John 17:19). The priest who offers is also the one through whom others are fed (John 6:51).</p>",
    "23": "<p>From the basket of unleavened bread — a loaf, a thick loaf with oil, and a wafer — taken together with the ordination ram portions. The combination of bread and meat in the wave offering anticipates the Lord's Supper's combination of bread and cup. The ordination meal that consecrates the Aaronic priests for their ministry becomes the Lord's Supper that constitutes the new-covenant community as 'a royal priesthood' (1 Pet 2:9) consecrated for their ministry of worship and witness.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'Put all these in the hands of Aaron and his sons and have them wave them before the LORD as a wave offering.' The wave offering (<em>t'nufah</em>) — presented before YHWH with a back-and-forth motion — represents presenting the offering to God and receiving it back. Jesus presents himself to the Father in the cross and is received back in the resurrection. Hebrews 9:11-12: he 'went through the greater and more perfect tabernacle... and... entered the most holy place once for all by his own blood' — the ultimate wave offering, presented and received.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'Then take them from their hands and burn them on the altar along with the burnt offering for a pleasing aroma to the LORD.' The ordination portions are burned on top of the burnt offering — the ordination-consecration burns with the total-consecration. The two fires merge. In Christ, the total self-giving (burnt offering) and the consecration of ministry (ordination offering) are one act: the cross is simultaneously the total offering to God and the inauguration of the eternal high-priestly ministry. The two fires merge into one altar.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'After you take the breast of the ordination ram belonging to Aaron, wave it before the LORD as a wave offering; it will be your share.' The breast — the portion of the heart — belongs to Moses (the one performing the ordination) as his share. The priestly portions are distributed: heart to the ordaining leader, thigh to the ordained. The ordination creates a sharing community where each participant receives a portion of the sacrifice. The Lord's Supper creates the same distributed community: 'Is not the cup of thanksgiving a participation in the blood of Christ? And is not the bread that we break a participation in the body of Christ?' (1 Cor 10:16).</p>",
    "27": "<p>'Consecrate those parts of the ordination ram that belong to Aaron and his sons: the breast that was waved and the thigh that was presented.' The wave breast and the lifted thigh are the portions that belong to the priesthood in all future peace offerings. The priestly share of the sacrifice — the ongoing provision that sustains the priests in their service — is the type of Christ's ongoing provision for the church through the Eucharist. The priest is fed by the very sacrifice he offers; the church is nourished by the body and blood of the one it commemorates.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'This is always to be the regular share from the Israelites for Aaron and his sons. It is the contribution the Israelites are to make to the LORD from their fellowship offerings.' The priestly share is constitutionally established — not a favor but a right enshrined in the covenant. 1 Corinthians 9:14: 'The Lord has commanded that those who preach the gospel should receive their living from the gospel.' The NT establishes the pattern of the Levitical priesthood for the support of gospel ministers, grounded in the same principle: those who serve at the altar share in what is offered.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'Aaron's sacred garments will belong to his descendants after him, so that they can be anointed and ordained in them.' The vestments pass from father to son — the priesthood is inherited through succession. Hebrews 7:23: 'Now there have been many of those priests, since death prevented them from continuing in office.' The inheritance of vestments by each successive high priest encodes the problem: mortality requires succession, which means the priesthood is never fully permanent. Only a priest who never dies can hold the office permanently — and that priest is the 'Son who has been made perfect for ever' (Heb 7:28).</p>",
    "30": "<p>'The son who succeeds him as priest and comes to the tent of meeting to minister in the holy place is to wear them seven days.' The seven-day re-ordination with the inherited vestments. Seven days = the complete cycle, the full period. The new high priest serves a week in the vestments before beginning independent ministry. Christ's priestly ministry is inaugurated not by seven days but by the once-for-all 'one sacrifice for sins for all time' (Heb 10:12) after which he 'sat down at the right hand of God.' The period of ordination gives way to the enthronement of the eternal priest.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'Take the ram of the ordination and cook the meat in a sacred place.' The ordination ram's meat is cooked in the holy precinct — the priestly meal is inseparable from the holy space. The Lord's Supper is similarly tied to sacred context: 'When you come together as a church' (1 Cor 11:18); 'Is not the cup of thanksgiving for which we give thanks a participation in the blood of Christ?' (1 Cor 10:16). The covenant meal belongs to the covenant assembly gathered in Christ's name.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'At the entrance to the tent of meeting, Aaron and his sons are to eat the meat of the ram and the bread that is in the basket.' The ordination meal at the tent's entrance — the threshold of sacred space — is the priestly community's inaugural feast. The Last Supper is the new-covenant ordination meal: Jesus gives the disciples the bread and cup 'before he suffered' (Luke 22:15), inaugurating their priestly-apostolic ministry with the covenant meal. The entrance to the tent of meeting becomes the upper room; the ordination feast becomes the Eucharistic foundation.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'They are to eat these offerings by which atonement was made for their ordination and consecration. But no one else may eat them, because they are sacred.' The atonement-meal is restricted to those for whom atonement was made — the ordained. The Lord's Supper similarly presupposes covenant membership (1 Cor 11:27-29): the Eucharistic bread and cup are the sacred food of those who have been consecrated through baptism and faith. The exclusivity of the ordination meal is not elitism but the appropriate restriction of sacred food to those for whom it was offered.</p>",
    "34": "<p>'If any of the meat of the ordination ram or any bread is left over till morning, burn it up. It must not be eaten, because it is sacred.' Nothing of the sacred ordination meal may be profaned by carrying it into ordinary time. The total consumption that cannot be deferred mirrors Christ's 'it is finished' (John 19:30) — the sacrifice is complete, accomplished, not to be continued or supplemented. The burning of leftovers is the ritual enactment of the once-for-all completeness of the atonement.</p>",
    "35": "<p>'Do for Aaron and his sons everything I have commanded you, taking seven days to ordain them.' The complete seven-day ordination — the full cycle of consecration. The number seven signals completeness throughout Scripture (seven days of creation, seven of Passover, seven of Unleavened Bread). Christ's ordination was not seven days but his entire thirty-three-year life — the full cycle of human existence lived in perfect obedience — culminating in the cross, after which he is 'designated by God to be high priest in the order of Melchizedek' (Heb 5:10).</p>",
    "36": "<p>'Sacrifice a bull each day as a sin offering to make atonement. Purify the altar by making atonement for it, and anoint it to consecrate it.' Even the altar requires seven days of atonement-sacrifices before it can function as the locus of sacrifice. The instrument of atonement itself needs atonement — the altar is holy but imperfect, made by human hands. Christ's altar is his own body (Heb 13:10); it requires no purification because 'through the eternal Spirit he offered himself unblemished to God' (Heb 9:14). The altar that needs no seven-day consecration is the perfect Mediator himself.</p>",
    "37": "<p>'For seven days make atonement for the altar and consecrate it. Then the altar will be most holy, and whatever touches it will be holy.' The altar becomes the source of holiness — whatever touches it is consecrated. Jesus reverses the normal direction: when the unclean touch him, he does not become unclean but they become clean (the leper, Matt 8:3; the bleeding woman, Matt 9:20-22). The consecrated altar of the OT communicates holiness by contact; Christ the living altar communicates holiness by faith-contact to all who come to him.</p>",
    "38": "<p>'This is what you are to offer on the altar regularly each day: two lambs a year old.' The <em>tamid</em> — the daily regular offering — two lambs, morning and evening. The tamid structures Israel's worship day: it begins and ends with the lamb. Hebrews 7:27 makes the contrast explicit: 'Unlike the other high priests, he does not need to offer sacrifices day after day, first for his own sins, and then for the sins of the people. He sacrificed for their sins once for all when he offered himself.' The daily two-lamb tamid is what the Aaronic priesthood requires; Christ's once-for-all self-offering replaces the daily lambs.</p>",
    "39": "<p>'Offer one in the morning and the other at twilight.' The day is bookended by the tamid lambs — the day begins and ends under sacrifice, under the covering of atonement. The Christian's day begins and ends under the cross — 'forgive us our sins, as we also forgive' in the morning (Matt 6:12) and 'the evening sacrifice' of praise and confession (Ps 141:2). But the ground of these daily prayers is not a daily lamb but the once-for-all cross that covers every morning and every evening.</p>",
    "40": "<p>With the morning lamb: a grain offering of finest flour with olive oil and a drink offering of wine. The grain, oil, and wine that accompany the lamb constitute the full range of agricultural bounty — the whole harvest in service of the sacrifice. The Lord's Supper uses bread (grain) and wine (drink offering) as the memorial elements — the same agricultural offerings that accompanied the tamid lamb, now accompanying the once-for-all Lamb in the memorial that the church maintains until he comes.</p>",
    "41": "<p>'Sacrifice the other lamb at twilight with the same grain offering and drink offering... This is a food offering, an aroma pleasing to the LORD.' The evening sacrifice closes the day with the same elements as the morning — the consistency of the covenant relationship. Paul in 1 Thessalonians 5:17: 'pray continually.' The bookending of the day with sacrifice (tamid) is the OT form of the NT's unceasing prayer — the life of the covenant community is lived under the covering of the priestly offering from first light to last.</p>",
    "42": "<p>'For the generations to come this burnt offering is to be made regularly at the entrance to the tent of meeting, before the LORD. There I will meet with you and speak to you.' The tent of meeting (ohel mo'ed — 'tent of appointed meeting') is the place of the divine-human encounter structurally incorporated into Israel's life through the tamid. Jesus is the final meeting-place — 'I am the way and the truth and the life. No one comes to the Father except through me' (John 14:6). The tent where YHWH meets with Israel is fulfilled in the person of the Son who is himself the locus of the divine-human encounter.</p>",
    "43": "<p>'There also I will meet with the Israelites, and the place will be consecrated by my glory.' The divine presence consecrates the meeting place — not the architecture but the divine glory (kavod) makes the tent holy. John 1:14: 'The Word became flesh and made his dwelling (<em>eskenos</em> — pitched his tent) among us. We have seen his glory (<em>doxa</em>), the glory of the one and only Son.' The tabernacle's glory is the type; the incarnate Son's glory is the antitype. Where Christ is, the place is consecrated — not a building but a person.</p>",
    "44": "<p>'So I will consecrate the tent of meeting and the altar and will consecrate Aaron and his sons to serve me as priests.' The consecration flows from divine initiative: YHWH consecrates, not human effort. John 17:17-19: 'Sanctify them by the truth; your word is truth... For them I sanctify myself, that they too may be truly sanctified.' The divine consecration of the priests (v.44) is the type of Christ's self-consecration through which the new-covenant priests are sanctified. The source of all holiness is the same divine initiative.</p>",
    "45": "<p>'Then I will dwell among the Israelites and be their God.' The covenant formula reached its OT climax: divine dwelling with the covenant people as their God. John 1:14: 'the Word became flesh and dwelt (<em>eskenosen</em> — tabernacled) among us.' The incarnation is the fulfillment of v.45 in a mode more direct than the tabernacle could achieve — not a cloud of glory in a tent but the Son of God in human flesh, walking among his people as their Emmanuel ('God with us,' Matt 1:23). The goal of the entire tabernacle system is achieved personally in the Incarnation.</p>",
    "46": "<p>'They will know that I am the LORD their God, who brought them out of Egypt so that I might dwell among them.' The goal of the Exodus is stated: not merely liberation from slavery but divine dwelling with humanity. The entire Exodus — the plagues, the Passover, the sea-crossing, the Sinai covenant, the tabernacle instructions — moves toward this single purpose: God dwelling with his people. The NT fulfillment moves through three stages: the incarnation (John 1:14), the indwelling Spirit (John 14:17; 1 Cor 3:16), and the final consummation (Rev 21:3: 'God's dwelling place is now among the people'). The 'I will dwell among them' of Exodus 29:46 is the great promise that drives the entire biblical narrative to its conclusion in the new creation.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'exodus')
    merge_comm(c, EXODUS)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'exodus', c)
    print('Exodus 28-29 mkt-christ commentary written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
